{{Infobox artwork | title = {{wikidata|label|Q9372005}} | image = {{wikidata|property|raw|Q9372005|P18}} | image_upright = | alt = | caption = | painting_alignment = | other_language_1 = | other_title_1 = | other_language_2 = | other_title_2 = | wikidata = Q20170935 | artist = {{wikidata|property|Q9372005|P170}} | year = {{wikidata|property|Q9372005|P571}} | completion_date = <!-- For a more specific date (post-1583): {{start date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} --> | catalogue = | medium = {{wikidata|property|Q9372005|P186}} | movement = {{wikidata|property|Q9372005|P135}} | subject = | height_metric = {{wikidata|property|raw|Q9372005|P2048}} | width_metric = {{wikidata|property|raw|Q9372005|P2049}} | length_metric = {{wikidata|property|raw|Q9372005|P2610}} | height_imperial = <!-- (i.e. in imperial units) --> | width_imperial = | length_imperial = | diameter_metric = | diameter_imperial = | metric_unit = cm <!-- Change to m for artworks measured by meters --> | imperial_unit = in <!-- Change to ft for artworks measured by feet --> | dimensions = | dimensions_ref = | weight = {{wikidata|property|Q9372005|P2067}} | designation = | condition = | museum = {{wikidata|property|Q9372005|P195}} | city = | coordinates = <!-- Only use for the known location of the artwork within the institution, i.e. not for the location of the institution where the artwork is kept. Otherwise leave blank or omit: {{coord|LAT|LON|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} --> | owner = | accession = {{wikidata|property|Q9372005|P217}} | website = [{{#if: {{wikidata|property|Q9372005|P3634}} | http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/{{wikidata|property|Q9372005|P3634}} | {{wikidata|property|Q9372005|P973}}}} {{wikidata|property|Q9372005|P195}}] | preceded_by = <!-- preceding work by the same artist --> | followed_by = <!-- next work by the same artist --> }} '''''Venus and Mars''''' is an [[Italian Renaissance]] painting by [[Paolo Veronese]].
The painting was commissioned by [[Rudolf II, Holy Roman Emperor|Emperor Rudolph]] and was one of three mythological and love-themed works commissioned by the artist. The other two are at the [[Frick Collection]] in New York: ''The Allegory of Virtue and Performance'' and ''Allegory of the Source of Wisdom and Power''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/437891|title=Paolo Veronese (Paolo Caliari) {{!}} Mars and Venus United by Love {{!}} The Met|website=The Metropolitan Museum of Art, i.e. The Met Museum|access-date=2017-06-26}}</ref> It deals with the romantic love of the Roman goddess of love [[Venus (mythology)|Venus]] and the god of war [[Mars (mythology)|Mars]], as described in the [[Ovid]]'s ''[[Metamorphoses]]''.
== Description == The act of meeting the two lovers takes place in idyllic, peaceful scenery. On the left stands a naked goddess, with her left hand embracing the arrival of Mars, sitting in front of her in armor. The right hand of Venus rests on the breast from which the milk flows out, emphasizing its femininity. On the right side there is a war horse of god of war, tamed by one of the lovers. Its silhouette is based on antique horse monuments. The underlined musculature of the animal expresses his strength, and his inclined head and calm eyes soften his image. The two putti shown are the key to the interpretation of the work. The first taming horse symbolizes the subduction of the love desires of the god of Mars, the control over passions.<ref>Allan Burroughs, ''Alan Criticism from a Laboratory'', Little Brown, Boston 1938, s.93-94, za. H. Rachlin</ref> The second putto, which tied the ribbon around Venus' legs, symbolizes the union of lovers into eternal love and harmony in a time without wars. Milk from the breast of Venus symbolizes the wealth of peace, which is the food for humanity.<ref>H. Rachlin ''Skandale, wandale i niezwykłe opowieści o wielkich dziełach sztuki'' s.55</ref> The artist signed on a stone disc: "PAVLUS VERONENSIS F".
== Interpretation == Veronese kept the balance of composition. Each character has its own space, unmade by accidental elements. To get this picture the painter repeatedly repainted his work. X-ray study described by Alan Burroughs in his book ''Art Criticism from a Laboratory'' showed that the arrangement of Venus's body was different and was probably covered with drapery pulling downwards. The innocent cherub was not in the original version [2]. It is not clear why Veronese made these changes. Celebrity Venus had a completely different tone, more prudish, and lack of amora would give the scene a more mundane erotic meaning of meeting two lovers. The small changes made by the painter gave the work a new dimension of spirituality and innocence [3]
== Provenance == In 1621, a catalog was made of the works in the collection of Rudolf II in [[Prague Castle]]. Over the centuries, the painting had many owners and circulated throughout Europe. It was in the possession of [[Ferdinand III of Habsburg]], and after the Swedes' invasion of Prague in 1648, it entered the collection of Queen [[Christina of Sweden]] and was taken with her in her Roman exile. It then went to the [[Erba-Odescalchi|Odescalchici family]], later to the famous [[Orleans Collection]] in Paris. In 1792, it went to the [[Edouard de Walckiers]] collection in Brussels but returned to Paris in 1798, and then went to London. After several English owners, in 1910 it was sold to the Metropolitan Museum of Art.
